<p>How many States’ agencies’ guidance accurately notifies parents and students of their transfer of rights options? </p>

 

<p>Many, if not most, state educational agencies’ guidance fail to accurately describe their transfer of rights policies. Importantly, many state educational agencies fail to notify parents and students of their right to avoid rights transfer by executing powers of attorney for educational decisions. This, despite the federal Department of Education’s clear instructions in 2006 that post transfer adult students may assign educational rights through “a power of attorney or similar grant of authority,” provided that State so allow. Federal Register, Vol. 71, No. 156 (August 14, 2006) at p. 46713.  </p>

<h3>State-Specific Questions </h3>

<p>Is there a law or regulation clearly stating if parents’ IDEA rights transfer to adult students? </p>

<p>Is there a law or regulation clearly stating if parents’ IDEA rights transfer to incarcerated students? </p>

<p>Does the law or regulation clearly state that parents have a right to notice post transfer? </p>

<p>Does the law or regulation clearly state that rights do not transfer to adult students with legal guardians or conservators? </p>

<p>Does the law or regulation clearly mention alternatives to guardianship?  </p>

<p>Is there a law or regulation creating a “special procedure” to appoint representatives for adult students deemed unable to give informed consent?  </p>

<p>Do parents lose the right to make a due process complaint or to sue if their adult children’s right to FAPE is violated? </p>

<p>Does state educational agency guidance clearly explain the applicable laws and/or regulations regarding transfer of rights?</p>
